The correct answer is \textbf{b = 2}

The slower, albeit more constructive way, to solve this is to set up a
system of equations consisting of the following

\begin{align*}
n &\equiv 1 \mod 2  \quad n \equiv 2 \mod{3} \quad n \equiv 3 \mod{4} \\
n &\equiv 4 \mod{5} \quad n \equiv 5 \mod{6} \quad n \equiv 0 \mod{7}  
\end{align*}

Now we just crunch condition by condition. Notice that some of these
equations are redundant. In fact the cases modulo 2 and modulo 6 can be
reduced from the cases modulo 4 and from combining the modulo 2 and 3
cases respectively. Hence we need only consider the equations

\begin{align*}
n \equiv 2 \mod 3 \quad n \equiv 3 \mod 4 \quad n \equiv 4 \mod 5 \quad n \equiv 0 \mod 7  
\end{align*}

For the remaining steps, let $\displaystyle k_{i}$ be integers for each
$\displaystyle i=1..4$ as needed. The first equation tells us that

\begin{align*}
n = 2 + 3k_{1}
\end{align*}

Plugging into the second yields
$\displaystyle 2 + 3k_{1} \equiv 3 \mod 4$ which implies that
$\displaystyle k_{1} \equiv 3 \mod 4$. This says
$\displaystyle k_{1} = 3 + 4k_{2}$. Plugging into the equation above
yields

\begin{align*}
n = 2 + 3k_{1} = 2 + 3(3 + 4k_{2}) = 11 + 12k_{2}
\end{align*}

Next, into the third equation yields
$\displaystyle 11 + 12k_{2} \equiv 4 \mod 5$ which implies that
$k_{2} \equiv 4 \mod 5$. This says $\displaystyle k_{2} = 4 + 5k_{3}$ .
Hence, plugging into the equation above yields

\begin{align*}
n = 11 + 12k_{2} = 11 + 12(4 + 5k_{3}) = 59 + 60k_{3}
\end{align*}

Lastly, into the fourth equation yields
$\displaystyle 59 + 60k_{3} \equiv 0 \mod 7$ which implies that
$\displaystyle k_{3} \equiv 1 \mod 7$. This says
$\displaystyle k_{3} = 1 + 7k_{4}$. Hence, plugging into the equation
above yields

\begin{align*}
n = 59 + 60k_{3} = 59 + 60(1 + 7k_{4}) = 119 + 420k_{4}
\end{align*}

Thus, in order for all these conditions to be satisfied, we need
\emph{n} to be congruent to 119 modulo 420. The minimum such number is
119. Modulo 13, we see that the answer is 2.

